        "text": ". Rather, \"the tail.\" Oriental sheep have very commonly a broad fat tail, which weighs from six to twenty  pounds, and is sometimes laid upon a little cart with two wheels, which the sheep drags after it (Herod. 3:113; Leo African. 9. p. 293 A; Fellows, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Asia Minor",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 10; Gesenius ad voc. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "אליה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). There is no doubt that a \"tail\" of this kind is here meant. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The caul",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Rather, \"the membrane.\" See the comment on ver 13. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The right shoulder",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Or \"leg,\" according to some. The difference is not important. Exodus 29:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
